#######################
## Initialization

DOCUMENT();
loadMacros(
	"PG.pl",
	"PGbasicmacros.pl",
	"PGanswermacros.pl",
	"PGcourse.pl"
	);


TEXT(beginproblem());

###################################
# Setup

$a=random(3,5,1);
$b=random(2,4,1);
$c=random(2,5,1);
$d=random(1,3,1);
$rand=random(1,2,1);
if ($rand==1)
	{
	$p=2;
	$den=6;
	$od = 8;
	$piv = (pi)**2/$den;
	}
else
	{
	$p=4;
	$den=90;
	$od = 96;
	$piv = (pi)**4/$den;
	};

###################################
# Main text

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
Leonhard Euler was able to calculate the exact sum of the \(p\)-series with \(p=$p\):

\[\sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{1}{n^$p} = \frac{\pi^$p}{$den}.\]

Use this fact to find the sum of each series. $BR

$BR
\(\displaystyle \sum_{n=$a}^\infty \frac{1}{n^$p} = \)  \{ans_rule(20)\}
$BR

$BR
\(\displaystyle \sum_{n=$b}^\infty \frac{1}{(n+$d)^$p} = \)  \{ans_rule(20)\}
$BR

$BR
\(\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{1}{($c n)^$p} = \)  \{ans_rule(20)\}
$BR

$BR
\(\displaystyle \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{1}{(2n + 1)^$p} = \) \{ans_rule(20)\}
$BR

EOT

###################################
## Answer evaluation

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$ans1=$piv;
for ( $n = 1; $n < $a; $n++ )
	{
	$ans1 = $ans1 - 1/($n**$p);
	};

$ans2=$piv;
for ( $n = 1; $n < $b+$d; $n++ )
	{
	$ans2 = $ans2 - 1/($n**$p);
	};

$ans3=$piv/($c**$p);
$ans4 = (pi)**$p/$od;

ANS(num_cmp($ans1));
ANS(num_cmp($ans2));
ANS(num_cmp($ans3));
ANS(num_cmp($ans4));

ENDDOCUMENT();
